<DOC><DOCNO> AP880311-0286 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0942EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Stocks     03-11 0166</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks,0173</SECOND><HEAD>Oil Shares Buck Overall Negative Trend</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The London stock market remained largely depressedFriday following a steep fall on Wall Street, but oil shares buckedthe trend in heavy trading.   At 2 p.m. local time, the Financial Times Index of 100 leadingshares hit the low for the day of 1814.4 points, down 20.2.   The Financial Times 30-share index was down 23.1 points at1,449.2. Volume was a high 502.5 million shares.   After a steep fall in New York, the Dow Jones industrial averageclosed off 48.24 points at 2,026.03.   Oil stocks, however, proved an exception with heavy tradingcontinuing in British Petroleum shares. Total trading in thecompany amounted to more than a quarter of total stock exchangevolume.   The Kuwait Investment Office confirmed Friday it raised itsstake in the company to 21.25 percent, or 1.269 billion shares. Thenew stake broke the 20 percent ceiling British Petroleum had viewedas an acceptable holding for the Kuwait office.</TEXT></DOC>